   "source": [
    "# Lecture # 2 Modeling \n",
    "# Business Case: Energy Efficiency Analysis for a Manufacturing Plant\n",
    "You are a consultant hired by a manufacturing plant to analyze its energy efficiency. The plant produces combustion derivatives. To perform quality and purity control of the products, the management is concerned about the high costs concerning gathering the sample data. Testing samples are as expensive as commercial samples. Therefore the board wants to reduce and optimize the costs in the quality analsis, without omiting the essential information or generating any false positive in the conclusion. \n",
    "### Your task: \n",
    "Analyze the provided dataset (\"lecture_data.csv\") and provide insights to optimize and minimize overall analysis costs (ignore the units. All samples are taken in the same scales).\n",
    "\n",
    "----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "### Dataset Description:\n",
    "#### Consumption: \n",
    "The amount of raw materials consumed during the production process.\n",
    "#### Time Required: \n",
    "The time required to complete the production process by the machines.\n",
    "#### Energy: \n",
    "The energy consumption during the production process.\n",
    "#### Costs: \n",
    "The labor and additional transportation costs inside the manufacturing plant.\n",
    "\n",
    "----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n",
    "### Business Objectives and Recomendations\n",
    "#### Gathering Costs\n",
    "The collection of each variables exponentiates the total costs of the sample. Each addiontal collected variable dobles the cost production.\n",
    "#### Production Time Optimization:\n",
    "Analyze the relation between time required and consumption to identify if there's an opportunity to optimize the data collection without compromising quality."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "17ac1e78",
   "metadata": {},

    "# Imports\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from sklearn.decomposition import PCA\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "b8433fb9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Initial Naiv view\n",
    "fig_initial, ax_initial = plt.subplots(ncols = 2, figsize = (18, 9))\n",
    "\n",
    "ax_initial[0].scatter(data[\"consumption\"], data[\"time_required\"], s = 100)\n",
    "ax_initial[0].set_ylabel(\"consumption\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_initial[0].set_xlabel(\"time_required\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_initial[0].arrow(0, 0, 60, 0, width = 0.05, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\")\n",
    "ax_initial[0].arrow(0, 0, 0, 40, width = 0.05, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\")\n",
    "ax_initial[0].grid()\n",
    "\n",
    "ax_initial[1].scatter(data[\"time_required\"], data[\"costs\"], s = 100)\n",
    "ax_initial[1].set_ylabel(\"time_required\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_initial[1].set_xlabel(\"costs\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_initial[1].arrow(0, 0, 60, 0, width = 0.05, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\")\n",
    "ax_initial[1].arrow(0, 0, 0, 140, width = 0.05, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\")\n",
    "ax_initial[1].grid()"
   ]

    "## Phase Three: Build Model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "124e077a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Normalize the data to make sure that every variable is normally distributed.\n",
    "print(\"before normalising\", data.head(5))\n",
    "X = data[[\"consumption\", \"time_required\", \"energy\", \"costs\"]].values\n",
    "X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X) # normalizing the features\n",
    "print(\"\\nafter normalisation\")\n",
    "print(X[:5, :])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "2247913c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Apply the technique\n",
    "pca = PCA(n_components=2)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit and transform the data\n",
    "X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "9872b22e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Print the transformed data (principal components)\n",
    "print(\"\\nTransformed Data (Principal Components):\")\n",
    "print(X_pca)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "269eba37",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Understand the Variance (Eigenvalues)\n",
    "print(\"Eigenvalues\")\n",
    "print(pca.explained_variance_)\n",
    "print(\"\\nExplained Variance Ratio:\")\n",
    "print(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "282312a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Plot the Reduced dimensional Dataset \n",
    "print(\"The eigenvectors are\", pca.components_)\n",
    "x_mid = np.mean(X[:,0])\n",
    "y_mid = np.mean(X[:,1])\n",
    "\n",
    "fig_overlapped, ax_overlapped = plt.subplots(figsize = (9, 9))\n",
    "ax_overlapped.scatter(X[:,0], X[:,1], s = 100, label = 'Points')\n",
    "ax_overlapped.set_ylabel(\"Y - Coordinates\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_overlapped.set_xlabel(\"X - Coordinates\", fontsize = 20)\n",
    "ax_overlapped.arrow(0, 0, 1, 0, width = 0.025, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\", label = \"Original Coordinates\")\n",
    "ax_overlapped.arrow(0, 0, 0, 1, width = 0.025, length_includes_head = True, color = \"black\")\n",
    "ax_overlapped.scatter([x_mid], [y_mid], s = 200, c = \"red\", label = \"Center of Gravity\")\n",
    "ax_overlapped.arrow(x_mid, y_mid, \n",
    "                    pca.explained_variance_[0]*pca.components_[0,0], pca.explained_variance_[0]*pca.components_[0,1], \n",
    "                    width = 0.025, length_includes_head = True, color = \"orange\", label = \"PC Main Axe\")\n",
    "ax_overlapped.legend(loc='upper left', fontsize = 15)\n",
    "ax_overlapped.grid()"
   ]
  },

   ]

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "459ed5a0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Assess the model (Task List):\n",
    "#### Consider whether a models results are easily deployable? \n",
    "Yes. The model is easy to execute and does not requiere any addional costs to implement.\n",
    "#### Do they meet the goals established during the understanding phase?\n",
    "Yes. Regarding the Production-Time and consumption relation, The results indicate a latent and significant correlation, this is follows from the fact that one dimension gathers more than 90% of the whole variance.  The 2 dimensional model capture the most essential information in the Dataset and with 97% total information, there is no significant information loss. Furthermore, displayed is graphically.\n",
    "#### Do you find relevance in particular results?\n",
    "Yes. The model can be resumed to one feature combining all the 4, since with one single feature we gather more than 70% of the variance.\n",
    "#### How this result can affect your business?\n",
    "Reducing the measured variables to 1 instead from 4, will directly impact the cost structure and levels of the samples. Interestingly, with one feature the quality is not compromised, since the first component superates the trashhold for our quality check (above 70%).\n",
    "#### Which Variable should you take to reduce the cost analysis?\n",
    "![image.png](attachment:image.png)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "d400e5a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "loadings = pca.components_.T*np.sqrt(pca.explained_variance_)\n",
    "print(\"correlation PC1 to consumption\",   loadings[0,0]*np.std(X[:,0]))\n",
    "print(\"correlation PC1 to time_required\", loadings[1,0]*np.std(X[:,1]))\n",
    "print(\"correlation PC1 to energy\",        loadings[2,0]*np.std(X[:,2]))\n",
    "print(\"correlation PC1 to costs\",         loadings[3,0]*np.std(X[:,3]))"
   ]
  },

    "#### Can you draw meaningful conclusions from this model? \n",

    "Yes, Seconds but the results are not strong enough to make conclusions (less than)\n",

    "### Assess the model (Task List):\n",
    "#### Consider whether a models results are easily deployable? \n",
    "Yes. The model is easy to execute and does not requiere any addional costs to implement.\n",
    "#### Do they meet the goals established during the understanding phase?\n",
    "No, the feature reduction shows that the business goals are not met. If we use the model to perform analysis we could lose important importation and maybe produce false positives.\n",
    "#### Do you find relevance in particular results?\n",
    "No, the feature number must be increased to gather the basic essential information just 33% of the information.\n",
    "#### How this result can affect your business?\n",
    "Reducing the measured variables to 1 instead from 4, will directly impact the analysis of the sample in a negative way. The cumulated variance suggests that not all essential information about the product in contained in the reduced dataset."
